[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Let $X\colon \Omega \to \mathbb {R}$ be a random variable in some probability space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},\mathbb {P} )$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] We wish to estimate the expected value of X under $\mathbb {P}$ , denoted $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] The basic idea of importance sampling is to sample from a different distribution to lower the variance of the estimation of $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ , or when sampling directly from $\mathbb {P}$ is difficult.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] This is accomplished by first choosing a random variable $Y\geq 0$ such that $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[Y]=1$ and that $\mathbb {P}$ -almost everywhere $Y(\omega )\neq 0$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] When X is of constant sign over $\Omega$ , the best variable Y would clearly be $Y^{*}={\frac {X}{\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]}}\geq 0$ , so that $X/Y^{*}$ is the searched constant $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ and a single sample under $\mathbb {Q} ^{*}$ suffices to give its value.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Unfortunately we cannot take that choice, because $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ is precisely the value we are looking for!
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] therefore, a good probability change $\mathbb {Q}$ in importance sampling will redistribute the law of X so that its samples' frequencies are sorted directly according to their contributions in $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ as opposed to $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[1]$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Importance sampling is often used as a Monte Carlo integrator.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] When $\mathbb {P}$ is the uniform distribution over $\Omega =\mathbb {R}$ , the expectation $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ corresponds to the integral of the real function $X\colon \mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Such methods are frequently used to estimate posterior densities or expectations in state and/or parameter estimation problems in probabilistic models that are too hard to treat analytically.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Examples include Bayesian networks and importance weighted variational autoencoders.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] The fundamental issue in implementing importance sampling simulation is the choice of the biased distribution which encourages the important regions of the input variables.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Choosing or designing a good biased distribution is the "art" of importance sampling.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] The rewards for a good distribution can be huge run-time savings; the penalty for a bad distribution can be longer run times than for a general Monte Carlo simulation without importance sampling.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Consider X to be the sample and ${\frac {f(X)}{g(X)}}$ to be the likelihood ratio, where f is the probability density (mass) function of the desired distribution and g is the probability density (mass) function of the biased/proposal/sample distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Notice that when $X\geq 0$ , this variance becomes 0.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Consider estimating by simulation the probability $p_{t}\,$ of an event $X\geq t$ , where X is a random variable with cumulative distribution function $F(x)$ and probability density function $f(x)=F'(x)\,$ , where prime denotes derivative.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] A K -length independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) sequence $X_{i}\,$ is generated from the distribution F , and the number $k_{t}$ of random variables that lie above the threshold t are counted.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Note that the variance is low if $p_{t}\approx 1$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Importance sampling is concerned with the determination and use of an alternate density function $f_{*}\,$ (for X ), usually referred to as a biasing density, for the simulation experiment.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] This density allows the event ${X\geq t\ }$ to occur more frequently, so the sequence lengths K gets smaller for a given estimator variance.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Alternatively, for a given K , use of the biasing density results in a variance smaller than that of the conventional Monte Carlo estimate.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] From the definition of $p_{t}\,$ , we can introduce $f_{*}\,$ as below.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] is a likelihood ratio and is referred to as the weighting function.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] This is the importance sampling estimator of $p_{t}\,$ and is unbiased.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] That is, the estimation procedure is to generate i.i.d. samples from $f_{*}\,$ and for each sample which exceeds $t\,$ , the estimate is incremented by the weight $W\,$ evaluated at the sample value.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] The results are averaged over $K\,$ trials.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Now, the importance sampling problem then focuses on finding a biasing density $f_{*}\,$ such that the variance of the importance sampling estimator is less than the variance of the general Monte Carlo estimate.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] For some biasing density function, which minimizes the variance, and under certain conditions reduces it to zero, it is called an optimal biasing density function.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Although there are many kinds of biasing methods, the following two methods are most widely used in the applications of importance sampling.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Shifting probability mass into the event region ${X\geq t\ }$ by positive scaling of the random variable $X\,$ with a number greater than unity has the effect of increasing the variance (mean also) of the density function.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] This results in a heavier tail of the density, leading to an increase in the event probability.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Scaling is probably one of the earliest biasing methods known and has been extensively used in practice.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] It is simple to implement and usually provides conservative simulation gains as compared to other methods.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] In importance sampling by scaling, the simulation density is chosen as the density function of the scaled random variable $aX\,$ , where usually $a>1$ for tail probability estimation.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] While scaling shifts probability mass into the desired event region, it also pushes mass into the complementary region $X<t\,$ which is undesirable.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] If $X\,$ is a sum of $n\,$ random variables, the spreading of mass takes place in an $n\,$ dimensional space.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] The consequence of this is a decreasing importance sampling gain for increasing $n\,$ , and is called the dimensionality effect.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] A modern version of importance sampling by scaling is e.g. so-called sigma-scaled sampling (SSS) which is running multiple Monte Carlo (MC) analysis with different scaling factors.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] In opposite to many other high yield estimation methods (like worst-case distances WCD) SSS does not suffer much from the dimensionality problem.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Also addressing multiple MC outputs causes no degradation in efficiency.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] On the other hand, as WCD, SSS is only designed for Gaussian statistical variables, and in opposite to WCD, the SSS method is not designed to provide accurate statistical corners.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Another SSS disadvantage is that the MC runs with large scale factors may become difficult, e. g. due to model and simulator convergence problems.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] In addition, in SSS we face a strong bias-variance trade-off: Using large scale factors, we obtain quite stable yield results, but the larger the scale factors, the larger the bias error.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] If the advantages of SSS does not matter much in the application of interest, then often other methods are more efficient.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Another simple and effective biasing technique employs translation of the density function (and hence random variable) to place much of its probability mass in the rare event region.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Translation does not suffer from a dimensionality effect and has been successfully used in several applications relating to simulation of digital communication systems.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] It often provides better simulation gains than scaling.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] where $c\,$ is the amount of shift and is to be chosen to minimize the variance of the importance sampling estimator.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] The fundamental problem with importance sampling is that designing good biased distributions becomes more complicated as the system complexity increases.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Complex systems are the systems with long memory since complex processing of a few inputs is much easier to handle.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] In principle, the importance sampling ideas remain the same in these situations, but the design becomes much harder.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] A successful approach to combat this problem is essentially breaking down a simulation into several smaller, more sharply defined subproblems.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Then importance sampling strategies are used to target each of the simpler subproblems.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Examples of techniques to break the simulation down are conditioning and error-event simulation (EES) and regenerative simulation.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] In order to identify successful importance sampling techniques, it is useful to be able to quantify the run-time savings due to the use of the importance sampling approach.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] The performance measure commonly used is $\sigma _{MC}^{2}/\sigma _{IS}^{2}\,$ , and this can be interpreted as the speed-up factor by which the importance sampling estimator achieves the same precision as the MC estimator.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] This has to be computed empirically since the estimator variances are not likely to be analytically possible when their mean is intractable.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Other useful concepts in quantifying an importance sampling estimator are the variance bounds and the notion of asymptotic efficiency.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] One related measure is the so-called **Effective Sample Size** **(ESS)**.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Variance is not the only possible cost function for a simulation, and other cost functions, such as the mean absolute deviation, are used in various statistical applications.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Nevertheless, the variance is the primary cost function addressed in the literature, probably due to the use of variances in confidence intervals and in the performance measure $\sigma _{MC}^{2}/\sigma _{IS}^{2}\,$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] An associated issue is the fact that the ratio $\sigma _{MC}^{2}/\sigma _{IS}^{2}\,$ overestimates the run-time savings due to importance sampling since it does not include the extra computing time required to compute the weight function.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Hence, some people evaluate the net run-time improvement by various means.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Perhaps a more serious overhead to importance sampling is the time taken to devise and program the technique and analytically derive the desired weight function.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] When different proposal distributions, $g_{i}(x)$ , $i=1,\ldots ,n,$ are jointly used for drawing the samples $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n},$ different proper weighting functions can be employed (e.g., see ).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] In an adaptive setting, the proposal distributions, $g_{i,t}(x)$ , $i=1,\ldots ,n,$ and $t=1,\ldots ,T,$ are updated each iteration t of the adaptive importance sampling algorithm.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/importance-sampling] Hence, since a population of proposal densities is used, several suitable combinations of sampling and weighting schemes can be employed.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In statistics and statistical physics, the **Metropolis–Hastings algorithm** is a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) method for obtaining a sequence of random samples from a probability distribution from which direct sampling is difficult.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] New samples are added to the sequence in two steps: first a new sample is proposed based on the previous sample, then the proposed sample is either added to the sequence or rejected depending on the value of the probability distribution at that point.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The resulting sequence can be used to approximate the distribution (e.g. to generate a histogram) or to compute an integral (e.g. an expected value).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis–Hastings and other MCMC algorithms are generally used for sampling from multi-dimensional distributions, especially when the number of dimensions is high.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For single-dimensional distributions, there are usually other methods (e.g. adaptive rejection sampling) that can directly return independent samples from the distribution, and these are free from the problem of autocorrelated samples that is inherent in MCMC methods.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The algorithm is named in part for Nicholas Metropolis, the first coauthor of a 1953 paper, entitled *Equation of State Calculations by Fast Computing Machines*, with Arianna W.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Rosenbluth, Marshall Rosenbluth, Augusta H.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For many years the algorithm was known simply as the *Metropolis algorithm*.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The paper proposed the algorithm for the case of symmetrical proposal distributions, but in 1970, W.K.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Hastings extended it to the more general case.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The generalized method was eventually identified by both names, although the first use of the term "Metropolis-Hastings algorithm" is unclear.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Some controversy exists with regard to credit for development of the Metropolis algorithm.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis, who was familiar with the computational aspects of the method, had coined the term "Monte Carlo" in an earlier article with Stanisław Ulam, and led the group in the Theoretical Division that designed and built the MANIAC I computer used in the experiments in 1952.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] However, prior to 2003 there was no detailed account of the algorithm's development.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Shortly before his death, Marshall Rosenbluth attended a 2003 conference at LANL marking the 50th anniversary of the 1953 publication.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] At this conference, Rosenbluth described the algorithm and its development in a presentation titled "Genesis of the Monte Carlo Algorithm for Statistical Mechanics".
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Further historical clarification is made by Gubernatis in a 2005 journal article recounting the 50th anniversary conference.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Rosenbluth makes it clear that he and his wife Arianna did the work, and that Metropolis played no role in the development other than providing computer time.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This contradicts an account by Edward Teller, who states in his memoirs that the five authors of the 1953 article worked together for "days (and nights)".
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In contrast, the detailed account by Rosenbluth credits Teller with a crucial but early suggestion to "take advantage of statistical mechanics and take ensemble averages instead of following detailed kinematics".
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This, says Rosenbluth, started him thinking about the generalized Monte Carlo approach – a topic which he says he had discussed often with John Von Neumann.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Arianna Rosenbluth recounted (to Gubernatis in 2003) that Augusta Teller started the computer work, but that Arianna herself took it over and wrote the code from scratch.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In an oral history recorded shortly before his death, Rosenbluth again credits Teller with posing the original problem, himself with solving it, and Arianna with programming the computer.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm can draw samples from any probability distribution with probability density $P(x)$ , provided that we know a function $f(x)$ proportional to the density P and the values of $f(x)$ can be calculated.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The requirement that $f(x)$ must only be proportional to the density, rather than exactly equal to it, makes the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm particularly useful, because it removes the need to calculate the density's normalization factor, which is often extremely difficult in practice.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm generates a sequence of sample values in such a way that, as more and more sample values are produced, the distribution of values more closely approximates the desired distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These sample values are produced iteratively in such a way, that the distribution of the next sample depends only on the current sample value, which makes the sequence of samples a Markov chain.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Specifically, at each iteration, the algorithm proposes a candidate for the next sample value based on the current sample value.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Then, with some probability, the candidate is either accepted, in which case the candidate value is used in the next iteration, or it is rejected in which case the candidate value is discarded, and the current value is reused in the next iteration.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The probability of acceptance is determined by comparing the values of the function $f(x)$ of the current and candidate sample values with respect to the desired distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The method used to propose new candidates is characterized by the probability distribution $g(x\mid y)$ (sometimes written $Q(x\mid y)$ ) of a new proposed sample x given the previous sample y .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is called the *proposal density*, *proposal function*, or *jumping distribution*.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A common choice for $g(x\mid y)$ is a Gaussian distribution centered at y , so that points closer to y are more likely to be visited next, making the sequence of samples into a Gaussian random walk.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In the original paper by Metropolis et al.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] (1953), $g(x\mid y)$ was suggested to be a uniform distribution limited to some maximum distance from y .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] More complicated proposal functions are also possible, such as those of Hamiltonian Monte Carlo, Langevin Monte Carlo, or preconditioned Crank–Nicolson.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For the purpose of illustration, the Metropolis algorithm, a special case of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm where the proposal function is symmetric, is described below.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Let $f(x)$ be a function that is proportional to the desired probability density function $P(x)$ (a.k.a. a target distribution).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This algorithm proceeds by randomly attempting to move about the sample space, sometimes accepting the moves and sometimes remaining in place. $P(x)$ at specific point x is proportional to the iterations spent on the point by the algorithm.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Note that the acceptance ratio $\alpha$ indicates how probable the new proposed sample is with respect to the current sample, according to the distribution whose density is $P(x)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If we attempt to move to a point that is more probable than the existing point (i.e. a point in a higher-density region of $P(x)$ corresponding to an $\alpha >1\geq u$ ), we will always accept the move.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] However, if we attempt to move to a less probable point, we will sometimes reject the move, and the larger the relative drop in probability, the more likely we are to reject the new point.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Thus, we will tend to stay in (and return large numbers of samples from) high-density regions of $P(x)$ , while only occasionally visiting low-density regions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Intuitively, this is why this algorithm works and returns samples that follow the desired distribution with density $P(x)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] On the other hand, most simple rejection sampling methods suffer from the "curse of dimensionality", where the probability of rejection increases exponentially as a function of the number of dimensions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis–Hastings, along with other MCMC methods, do not have this problem to such a degree, and thus are often the only solutions available when the number of dimensions of the distribution to be sampled is high.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] As a result, MCMC methods are often the methods of choice for producing samples from hierarchical Bayesian models and other high-dimensional statistical models used nowadays in many disciplines.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In multivariate distributions, the classic Metropolis–Hastings algorithm as described above involves choosing a new multi-dimensional sample point.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] When the number of dimensions is high, finding the suitable jumping distribution to use can be difficult, as the different individual dimensions behave in very different ways, and the jumping width (see above) must be "just right" for all dimensions at once to avoid excessively slow mixing.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] An alternative approach that often works better in such situations, known as Gibbs sampling, involves choosing a new sample for each dimension separately from the others, rather than choosing a sample for all dimensions at once.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] That way, the problem of sampling from potentially high-dimensional space will be reduced to a collection of problems to sample from small dimensionality.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is especially applicable when the multivariate distribution is composed of a set of individual random variables in which each variable is conditioned on only a small number of other variables, as is the case in most typical hierarchical models.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The individual variables are then sampled one at a time, with each variable conditioned on the most recent values of all the others.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The purpose of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm is to generate a collection of states according to a desired distribution $P(x)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] To accomplish this, the algorithm uses a Markov process, which asymptotically reaches a unique stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ such that $\pi (x)=P(x)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A Markov process is uniquely defined by its transition probabilities $P(x'\mid x)$ , the probability of transitioning from any given state x to any other given state $x'$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] *Uniqueness of stationary distribution*: the stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ must be unique.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is guaranteed by ergodicity of the Markov process, which requires that every state must (1) be aperiodic—the system does not return to the same state at fixed intervals; and (2) be positive recurrent—the expected number of steps for returning to the same state is finite.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm involves designing a Markov process (by constructing transition probabilities) that fulfills the two above conditions, such that its stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ is chosen to be $P(x)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The approach is to separate the transition in two sub-steps; the proposal and the acceptance-rejection.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The proposal distribution $g(x'\mid x)$ is the conditional probability of proposing a state $x'$ given x , and the acceptance distribution $A(x',x)$ is the probability to accept the proposed state $x'$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The next step in the derivation is to choose an acceptance ratio that fulfills the condition above.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For this Metropolis acceptance ratio A , either $A(x',x)=1$ or $A(x,x')=1$ and, either way, the condition is satisfied.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] 3. if $u>A(x',x_{t})$ , then *reject* the new state, and copy the old state forward $x_{t+1}=x_{t}$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Provided that specified conditions are met, the empirical distribution of saved states $x_{0},\ldots ,x_{T}$ will approach $P(x)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The number of iterations ( T ) required to effectively estimate $P(x)$ depends on the number of factors, including the relationship between $P(x)$ and the proposal distribution and the desired accuracy of estimation.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For distribution on discrete state spaces, it has to be of the order of the autocorrelation time of the Markov process.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] An accessible account of the convergence theory for Metropolis–Hastings is given in.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] It is important to notice that it is not clear, in a general problem, which distribution $g(x'\mid x)$ one should use or the number of iterations necessary for proper estimation; both are free parameters of the method, which must be adjusted to the particular problem in hand.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A common use of Metropolis–Hastings algorithm is to compute an integral.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Specifically, consider a space $\Omega \subset \mathbb {R}$ and a probability distribution $P(x)$ over $\Omega$ , $x\in \Omega$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] where $A(x)$ is a (measurable) function of interest.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For example, consider a statistic $E(x)$ and its probability distribution $P(E)$ , which is a marginal distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Suppose that the goal is to estimate $P(E)$ for E on the tail of $P(E)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] and, thus, estimating $P(E)$ can be accomplished by estimating the expected value of the indicator function $A_{E}(x)\equiv \mathbf {1} _{E}(x)$ , which is 1 when $E(x)\in [E,E+\Delta E]$ and zero otherwise.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Because E is on the tail of $P(E)$ , the probability to draw a state x with $E(x)$ on the tail of $P(E)$ is proportional to $P(E)$ , which is small by definition.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm can be used here to sample (rare) states more likely and thus increase the number of samples used to estimate $P(E)$ on the tails.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This can be done e.g. by using a sampling distribution $\pi (x)$ to favor those states (e.g. $\pi (x)\propto e^{aE}$ with $a>0$ ).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Suppose that the most recent value sampled is $x_{t}$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] is the ratio of the proposal density in two directions (from $x_{t}$ to $x'$ and conversely).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is equal to 1 if the proposal density is symmetric.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Then the new state $x_{t+1}$ is chosen according to the following rules.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Markov chain is started from an arbitrary initial value $x_{0}$ , and the algorithm is run for many iterations until this initial state is "forgotten".
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These samples, which are discarded, are known as *burn-in*.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The remaining set of accepted values of x represent a sample from the distribution $P(x)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The algorithm works best if the proposal density matches the shape of the target distribution $P(x)$ , from which direct sampling is difficult, that is $g(x'\mid x_{t})\approx P(x')$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If a Gaussian proposal density g is used, the variance parameter $\sigma ^{2}$ has to be tuned during the burn-in period.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is usually done by calculating the *acceptance rate*, which is the fraction of proposed samples that is accepted in a window of the last N samples.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The desired acceptance rate depends on the target distribution, however it has been shown theoretically that the ideal acceptance rate for a one-dimensional Gaussian distribution is about 50%, decreasing to about 23% for an N -dimensional Gaussian target distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These guidelines can work well when sampling from sufficiently regular Bayesian posteriors as they often follow a multivariate normal distribution as can be established using the Bernstein–von Mises theorem.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If $\sigma ^{2}$ is too small, the chain will *mix slowly* (i.e., the acceptance rate will be high, but successive samples will move around the space slowly, and the chain will converge only slowly to $P(x)$ ).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] On the other hand, if $\sigma ^{2}$ is too large, the acceptance rate will be very low because the proposals are likely to land in regions of much lower probability density, so $a_{1}$ will be very small, and again the chain will converge very slowly.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] One typically tunes the proposal distribution so that the algorithms accepts on the order of 30% of all samples – in line with the theoretical estimates mentioned in the previous paragraph.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] MCMC can be used to draw samples from the posterior distribution of a statistical model.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] In mathematics, **Monte Carlo integration** is a technique for numerical integration using random numbers.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] It is a particular Monte Carlo method that numerically computes a definite integral.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] While other algorithms usually evaluate the integrand at a regular grid, Monte Carlo randomly chooses points at which the integrand is evaluated.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] This method is particularly useful for higher-dimensional integrals.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] There are different methods to perform a Monte Carlo integration, such as uniform sampling, stratified sampling, importance sampling, sequential Monte Carlo (also known as a particle filter), and mean-field particle methods.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] In numerical integration, methods such as the trapezoidal rule use a deterministic approach.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Monte Carlo integration, on the other hand, employs a non-deterministic approach: each realization provides a different outcome.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] In Monte Carlo, the final outcome is an approximation of the correct value with respective error bars, and the correct value is likely to be within those error bars.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Given the estimation of *I* from *QN*, the error bars of *QN* can be estimated by the sample variance using the unbiased estimate of the variance.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Since the sequence $\left\{\mathrm {E} (\sigma _{1}^{2}),\mathrm {E} (\sigma _{2}^{2}),\mathrm {E} (\sigma _{3}^{2}),\ldots \right\}$ is bounded due to being identically equal to *Var(f)*, as long as this is assumed finite, this variance decreases asymptotically to zero as 1/*N*.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] This is standard error of the mean multiplied with V .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] This result does not depend on the number of dimensions of the integral, which is the promised advantage of Monte Carlo integration against most deterministic methods that depend exponentially on the dimension.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] It is important to notice that, unlike in deterministic methods, the estimate of the error is not a strict error bound; random sampling may not uncover all the important features of the integrand that can result in an underestimate of the error.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] While the naive Monte Carlo works for simple examples, an improvement over deterministic algorithms can only be accomplished with algorithms that use problem-specific sampling distributions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] With an appropriate sample distribution it is possible to exploit the fact that almost all higher-dimensional integrands are very localized and only small subspace notably contributes to the integral.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] A large part of the Monte Carlo literature is dedicated in developing strategies to improve the error estimates.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] In particular, stratified sampling—dividing the region in sub-domains—and importance sampling—sampling from non-uniform distributions—are two examples of such techniques.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] A paradigmatic example of a Monte Carlo integration is the estimation of π.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] In the figure on the right, the relative error ${\tfrac {Q_{N}-\pi }{\pi }}$ is measured as a function of *N*, confirming the ${\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {N}}}$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The ordinary 'dividing by two' strategy does not work for multi-dimensions as the number of sub-volumes grows far too quickly to keep track.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Instead one estimates along which dimension a subdivision should bring the most dividends and only subdivides the volume along this dimension.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The stratified sampling algorithm concentrates the sampling points in the regions where the variance of the function is largest thus reducing the grand variance and making the sampling more effective, as shown on the illustration.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The popular MISER routine implements a similar algorithm.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The MISER algorithm is based on recursive stratified sampling.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] This technique aims to reduce the overall integration error by concentrating integration points in the regions of highest variance.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Hence the smallest error estimate is obtained by allocating sample points in proportion to the standard deviation of the function in each sub-region.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The MISER algorithm proceeds by bisecting the integration region along one coordinate axis to give two sub-regions at each step.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The direction is chosen by examining all *d* possible bisections and selecting the one which will minimize the combined variance of the two sub-regions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The variance in the sub-regions is estimated by sampling with a fraction of the total number of points available to the current step.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The same procedure is then repeated recursively for each of the two half-spaces from the best bisection.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The remaining sample points are allocated to the sub-regions using the formula for *Na* and *Nb*.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] This recursive allocation of integration points continues down to a user-specified depth where each sub-region is integrated using a plain Monte Carlo estimate.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] These individual values and their error estimates are then combined upwards to give an overall result and an estimate of its error.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Importance sampling provides a very important tool to perform Monte-Carlo integration.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The main result of importance sampling to this method is that the uniform sampling of ${\overline {\mathbf {x} }}$ is a particular case of a more generic choice, on which the samples are drawn from any distribution $p({\overline {\mathbf {x} }})$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The idea is that $p({\overline {\mathbf {x} }})$ can be chosen to decrease the variance of the measurement *QN*.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Consider the following example where one would like to numerically integrate a Gaussian function, centered at 0, with σ = 1, from −1000 to 1000.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Naturally, if the samples are drawn uniformly on the interval [−1000, 1000], only a very small part of them would be significant to the integral.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] This can be improved by choosing a different distribution from where the samples are chosen, for instance by sampling according to a Gaussian distribution centered at 0, with σ = 1.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Of course the "right" choice strongly depends on the integrand.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Intuitively, this says that if we pick a particular sample twice as much as other samples, we weight it half as much as the other samples.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] This estimator is naturally valid for uniform sampling, the case where $p({\overline {\mathbf {x} }})$ is constant.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm is one of the most used algorithms to generate ${\overline {\mathbf {x} }}$ from $p({\overline {\mathbf {x} }})$ , thus providing an efficient way of computing integrals.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The VEGAS algorithm approximates the exact distribution by making a number of passes over the integration region which creates the histogram of the function *f*.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Each histogram is used to define a sampling distribution for the next pass.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] Asymptotically this procedure converges to the desired distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] In order to avoid the number of histogram bins growing like *Kd*, the probability distribution is approximated by a separable function: $g(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots )=g_{1}(x_{1})g_{2}(x_{2})\ldots$ so that the number of bins required is only *Kd*.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] This is equivalent to locating the peaks of the function from the projections of the integrand onto the coordinate axes.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] The efficiency of VEGAS depends on the validity of this assumption.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] It is most efficient when the peaks of the integrand are well-localized.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] If an integrand can be rewritten in a form which is approximately separable this will increase the efficiency of integration with VEGAS.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-integration] VEGAS incorporates a number of additional features, and combines both stratified sampling and importance sampling.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three distinct problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and non-uniform random variate generation, available for modeling phenomena with significant input uncertainties, e.g. risk assessments for nuclear power plants.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often implemented using computer simulations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] They can provide approximate solutions to problems too complex for mathematical analysis.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The name comes from the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco, where the primary developer of the method, mathematician Stanisław Ulam, was inspired by his uncle's gambling habits.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in various fields of science, engineering, and mathematics, such as physics, chemistry, biology, statistics, artificial intelligence, finance, and cryptography.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] They have also been applied to social sciences, such as sociology, psychology, and political science.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been recognized as one of the most important and influential ideas of the 20th century, and they have enabled many scientific and technological breakthroughs.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods also have some limitations and challenges, such as the trade-off between accuracy and computational cost, the curse of dimensionality, the reliability of random number generators, and the verification and validation of the results.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Generate inputs randomly from a probability distribution over the domain.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Perform a deterministic computation of the outputs.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] For example, consider a quadrant (circular sector) inscribed in a unit square.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Uniformly scatter a given number of points over the square.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Count the number of points inside the quadrant, i.e. having a distance from the origin of less than 1.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The ratio of the inside-count and the total-sample-count is an estimate of the ratio of the two areas, ⁠π/4⁠.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In this procedure, the domain of inputs is the square that circumscribes the quadrant.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] One can generate random inputs by scattering grains over the square, then performing a computation on each input to test whether it falls within the quadrant.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Aggregating the results yields our final result, the approximation of π.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The approximation improves as more points are randomly placed in the whole square.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Uses of Monte Carlo methods require large amounts of random numbers, and their use benefitted greatly from pseudorandom number generators, which are far quicker to use than the tables of random numbers that had been previously employed.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often used in physical and mathematical problems and are most useful when it is difficult or impossible to use other approaches.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and generating draws from a probability distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Other examples include modeling phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs such as the calculation of risk in business and, in mathematics, evaluation of multidimensional definite integrals with complicated boundary conditions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In application to systems engineering problems (space, oil exploration, aircraft design, etc.), Monte Carlo–based predictions of failure, cost overruns and schedule overruns are routinely better than human intuition or alternative "soft" methods.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In principle, Monte Carlo methods can be used to solve any problem having a probabilistic interpretation.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] By the law of large numbers, integrals described by the expected value of some random variable can be approximated by taking the empirical mean (a.k.a. the 'sample mean') of independent samples of the variable.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] When the probability distribution of the variable is parameterized, mathematicians often use a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampler.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The central idea is to design a judicious Markov chain model with a prescribed stationary probability distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] That is, in the limit, the samples being generated by the MCMC method will be samples from the desired (target) distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] By the ergodic theorem, the stationary distribution is approximated by the empirical measures of the random states of the MCMC sampler.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In other problems, the objective is generating draws from a sequence of probability distributions satisfying a nonlinear evolution equation.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] These flows of probability distributions can always be interpreted as the distributions of the random states of a Markov process whose transition probabilities depend on the distributions of the current random states (see McKean–Vlasov processes, nonlinear filtering equation).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In other instances, a flow of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity arise (path spaces models with an increasing time horizon, Boltzmann–Gibbs measures associated with decreasing temperature parameters, and many others).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] These models can also be seen as the evolution of the law of the random states of a nonlinear Markov chain.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A natural way to simulate these sophisticated nonlinear Markov processes is to sample multiple copies of the process, replacing in the evolution equation the unknown distributions of the random states by the sampled empirical measures.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In contrast with traditional Monte Carlo and MCMC methodologies, these mean-field particle techniques rely on sequential interacting samples.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The terminology *mean field* reflects the fact that each of the *samples* (a.k.a. particles, individuals, walkers, agents, creatures, or phenotypes) interacts with the empirical measures of the process.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] When the size of the system tends to infinity, these random empirical measures converge to the deterministic distribution of the random states of the nonlinear Markov chain, so that the statistical interaction between particles vanishes.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Suppose one wants to know the expected value $\mu$ of a population (and knows that $\mu$ exists), but does not have a formula available to compute it.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The simple Monte Carlo method gives an estimate for $\mu$ by running n simulations and averaging the simulations' results.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] It has no restrictions on the probability distribution of the inputs to the simulations, requiring only that the inputs are randomly generated and are independent of each other and that $\mu$ exists.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A sufficiently large n will produce a value for m that is arbitrarily close to $\mu$ ; more formally, it will be the case that, for any $\epsilon >0$ , $|\mu -m|\leq \epsilon$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Suppose we want to know how many times we should expect to throw three eight-sided dice for the total of the dice throws to be at least T .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The dice throws are randomly distributed and independent of each other.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] If n is large enough, m will be within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ for any $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Choose the desired confidence level – the percent chance that, when the Monte Carlo algorithm completes, m is indeed within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Let z be the z -score corresponding to that confidence level.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Let $s^{2}$ be the estimated variance, sometimes called the "sample" variance; it is the variance of the results obtained from a relatively small number k of "sample" simulations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Note that, when the algorithm completes, $m_{k}$ is the mean of the k results.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] If $n\leq k$ , then $m_{k}=m$ ; sufficient sample simulations were done to ensure that $m_{k}$ is within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] An alternative formula can be used in the special case where all simulation results are bounded above and below.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Choose a value for $\epsilon$ that is twice the maximum allowed difference between $\mu$ and m .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Let $0<\delta <100$ be the desired confidence level, expressed as a percentage.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Let every simulation result $r_{1},r_{2},\ldots ,r_{i},\ldots ,r_{n}$ be such that $a\leq r_{i}\leq b$ for finite a and b .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Despite its conceptual and algorithmic simplicity, the computational cost associated with a Monte Carlo simulation can be staggeringly high.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In general the method requires many samples to get a good approximation, which may incur an arbitrarily large total runtime if the processing time of a single sample is high.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Although this is a severe limitation in very complex problems, the embarrassingly parallel nature of the algorithm allows this large cost to be reduced (perhaps to a feasible level) through parallel computing strategies in local processors, clusters, cloud computing, GPU, FPGA, etc.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Before the Monte Carlo method was developed, simulations tested a previously understood deterministic problem, and statistical sampling was used to estimate uncertainties in the simulations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations invert this approach, solving deterministic problems using probabilistic metaheuristics (see simulated annealing).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] An early variant of the Monte Carlo method was devised to solve the Buffon's needle problem, in which π can be estimated by dropping needles on a floor made of parallel equidistant strips.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In the 1930s, Enrico Fermi first experimented with the Monte Carlo method while studying neutron diffusion, but he did not publish this work.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In the late 1940s, Stanisław Ulam invented the modern version of the Markov Chain Monte Carlo method while he was working on nuclear weapons projects at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In 1946, nuclear weapons physicists at Los Alamos were investigating neutron diffusion in the core of a nuclear weapon.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Being secret, the work of von Neumann and Ulam required a code name.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A colleague of von Neumann and Ulam, Nicholas Metropolis, suggested using the name *Monte Carlo*, which refers to the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco where Ulam's uncle would borrow money from relatives to gamble.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods were central to the simulations required for further postwar development of nuclear weapons, including the design of the H-bomb, though severely limited by the computational tools at the time.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Von Neumann, Nicholas Metropolis and others programmed the ENIAC computer to perform the first fully automated Monte Carlo calculations, of a fission weapon core, in the spring of 1948.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In the 1950s Monte Carlo methods were used at Los Alamos for the development of the hydrogen bomb, and became popularized in the fields of physics, physical chemistry, and operations research.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Air Force were two of the major organizations responsible for funding and disseminating information on Monte Carlo methods during this time, and they began to find a wide application in many different fields.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The theory of more sophisticated mean-field type particle Monte Carlo methods had certainly started by the mid-1960s, with the work of Henry P.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] McKean Jr. on Markov interpretations of a class of nonlinear parabolic partial differential equations arising in fluid mechanics.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] An earlier pioneering article by Theodore E.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Harris and Herman Kahn, published in 1951, used mean-field genetic-type Monte Carlo methods for estimating particle transmission energies.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Mean-field genetic type Monte Carlo methodologies are also used as heuristic natural search algorithms (a.k.a. metaheuristic) in evolutionary computing.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The origins of these mean-field computational techniques can be traced to 1950 and 1954 with the work of Alan Turing on genetic type mutation-selection learning machines and the articles by Nils Aall Barricelli at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo, and more specifically diffusion Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mean-field particle Monte Carlo approximation of Feynman–Kac path integrals.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The origins of Quantum Monte Carlo methods are often attributed to Enrico Fermi and Robert Richtmyer who developed in 1948 a mean-field particle interpretation of neutron-chain reactions, but the first heuristic-like and genetic type particle algorithm (a.k.a.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Resampled or Reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods) for estimating ground state energies of quantum systems (in reduced matrix models) is due to Jack H.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In molecular chemistry, the use of genetic heuristic-like particle methodologies (a.k.a. pruning and enrichment strategies) can be traced back to 1955 with the seminal work of Marshall N.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The use of sequential Monte Carlo in advanced signal processing and Bayesian inference is more recent.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] It was in 1993, that Gordon et al., published in their seminal work the first application of a Monte Carlo resampling algorithm in Bayesian statistical inference.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The authors named their algorithm 'the bootstrap filter', and demonstrated that compared to other filtering methods, their bootstrap algorithm does not require any assumption about that state-space or the noise of the system.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Another pioneering article in this field was Genshiro Kitagawa's, on a related "Monte Carlo filter", and the ones by Pierre Del Moral and Himilcon Carvalho, Pierre Del Moral, André Monin and Gérard Salut on particle filters published in the mid-1990s.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Particle filters were also developed in signal processing in 1989–1992 by P.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Salut in the LAAS-CNRS in a series of restricted and classified research reports with STCAN (Service Technique des Constructions et Armes Navales), the IT company DIGILOG, and the LAAS-CNRS (the Laboratory for Analysis and Architecture of Systems) on radar/sonar and GPS signal processing problems.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] These Sequential Monte Carlo methodologies can be interpreted as an acceptance-rejection sampler equipped with an interacting recycling mechanism.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The mathematical foundations and the first rigorous analysis of these particle algorithms were written by Pierre Del Moral in 1996.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Branching type particle methodologies with varying population sizes were also developed in the end of the 1990s by Dan Crisan, Jessica Gaines and Terry Lyons, and by Dan Crisan, Pierre Del Moral and Terry Lyons.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Further developments in this field were described in 1999 to 2001 by P.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] There is no consensus on how *Monte Carlo* should be defined.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] For example, Ripley defines most probabilistic modeling as *stochastic simulation*, with *Monte Carlo* being reserved for Monte Carlo integration and Monte Carlo statistical tests.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Sawilowsky distinguishes between a simulation, a Monte Carlo method, and a Monte Carlo simulation: a simulation is a fictitious representation of reality, a Monte Carlo method is a technique that can be used to solve a mathematical or statistical problem.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo simulation uses repeated sampling to obtain the statistical properties of some phenomena.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Kalos and Whitlock point out that such distinctions are not always easy to maintain.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] For example, the emission of radiation from atoms is a natural stochastic process.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] It can be simulated directly, or its average behavior can be described by stochastic equations that can themselves be solved using Monte Carlo methods.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] "Indeed, the same computer code can be viewed simultaneously as a 'natural simulation' or as a solution of the equations by natural sampling." Convergence of the Monte Carlo simulation can be checked with the Gelman-Rubin statistic.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The main idea behind this method is that the results are computed based on repeated random sampling and statistical analysis.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation is, in fact, random experimentations, in the case that, the results of these experiments are not well known.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations are typically characterized by many unknown parameters, many of which are difficult to obtain experimentally.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation methods do not always require truly random numbers to be useful (although, for some applications such as primality testing, unpredictability is vital).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Many of the most useful techniques use deterministic, pseudorandom sequences, making it easy to test and re-run simulations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The only quality usually necessary to make good simulations is for the pseudo-random sequence to appear "random enough" in a certain sense.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] What this means depends on the application, but typically they should pass a series of statistical tests.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Testing that the numbers are uniformly distributed or follow another desired distribution when a large enough number of elements of the sequence are considered is one of the simplest and most common ones.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Weak correlations between successive samples are also often desirable/necessary.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Pseudo-random number sampling algorithms are used to transform uniformly distributed pseudo-random numbers into numbers that are distributed according to a given probability distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Low-discrepancy sequences are often used instead of random sampling from a space as they ensure even coverage and normally have a faster order of convergence than Monte Carlo simulations using random or pseudorandom sequences.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Methods based on their use are called quasi-Monte Carlo methods.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] No statistically significant difference was found between models generated with typical pseudorandom number generators and RDRAND for trials consisting of the generation of 107 random numbers.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] There are ways of using probabilities that are definitely not Monte Carlo simulations – for example, deterministic modeling using single-point estimates.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Each uncertain variable within a model is assigned a "best guess" estimate.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Scenarios (such as best, worst, or most likely case) for each input variable are chosen and the results recorded.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] By contrast, Monte Carlo simulations sample from a probability distribution for each variable to produce hundreds or thousands of possible outcomes.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The results are analyzed to get probabilities of different outcomes occurring.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] This is because the "what if" analysis gives equal weight to all scenarios (see quantifying uncertainty in corporate finance), while the Monte Carlo method hardly samples in the very low probability regions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The samples in such regions are called "rare events".
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are especially useful for simulating phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs and systems with many coupled degrees of freedom.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In statistical physics, Monte Carlo molecular modeling is an alternative to computational molecular dynamics, and Monte Carlo methods are used to compute statistical field theories of simple particle and polymer systems.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo methods solve the many-body problem for quantum systems.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In radiation materials science, the binary collision approximation for simulating ion implantation is usually based on a Monte Carlo approach to select the next colliding atom.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In experimental particle physics, Monte Carlo methods are used for designing detectors, understanding their behavior and comparing experimental data to theory.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In astrophysics, they are used in such diverse manners as to model both galaxy evolution and microwave radiation transmission through a rough planetary surface.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in the ensemble models that form the basis of modern weather forecasting.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in engineering for sensitivity analysis and quantitative probabilistic analysis in process design.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The need arises from the interactive, co-linear and non-linear behavior of typical process simulations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change relies on Monte Carlo methods in probability density function analysis of radiative forcing.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are used in various fields of computational biology, for example for Bayesian inference in phylogeny, or for studying biological systems such as genomes, proteins, or membranes.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The systems can be studied in the coarse-grained or *ab initio* frameworks depending on the desired accuracy.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Computer simulations allow monitoring of the local environment of a particular molecule to see if some chemical reaction is happening for instance.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In cases where it is not feasible to conduct a physical experiment, thought experiments can be conducted, e.g. breaking bonds, introducing impurities at specific sites, changing the local/global structure, or introducing external fields.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Path tracing, occasionally referred to as Monte Carlo ray tracing, renders a 3D scene by randomly tracing samples of possible light paths.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Repeated sampling of any given pixel will eventually cause the average of the samples to converge on the correct solution of the rendering equation, making it one of the most physically accurate 3D graphics rendering methods in existence.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The standards for Monte Carlo experiments in statistics were set by Sawilowsky.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] To provide implementations of hypothesis tests that are more efficient than exact tests such as permutation tests (which are often impossible to compute) while being more accurate than critical values for asymptotic distributions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] To provide a random sample from the posterior distribution in Bayesian inference.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] This sample then approximates and summarizes all the essential features of the posterior.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] To provide efficient random estimates of the Hessian matrix of the negative log-likelihood function that may be averaged to form an estimate of the Fisher information matrix.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also a compromise between approximate randomization and permutation tests.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] An approximate randomization test is based on a specified subset of all permutations (which entails potentially enormous housekeeping of which permutations have been considered).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo approach is based on a specified number of randomly drawn permutations (exchanging a minor loss in precision if a permutation is drawn twice—or more frequently—for the efficiency of not having to track which permutations have already been selected).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been developed into a technique called Monte-Carlo tree search that is useful for searching for the best move in a game.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Possible moves are organized in a search tree and many random simulations are used to estimate the long-term potential of each move.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A black box simulator represents the opponent's moves.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Expand the leaf node and choose one of its children.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Play a simulated game starting with that node.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Use the results of that simulated game to update the node and its ancestors.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The net effect, over the course of many simulated games, is that the value of a node representing a move will go up or down, hopefully corresponding to whether or not that node represents a good move.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo Tree Search has been used successfully to play games such as Go, Tantrix, Battleship, Havannah, and Arimaa.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The US Coast Guard utilizes Monte Carlo methods within its computer modeling software SAROPS in order to calculate the probable locations of vessels during search and rescue operations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Each simulation can generate as many as ten thousand data points that are randomly distributed based upon provided variables.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Search patterns are then generated based upon extrapolations of these data in order to optimize the probability of containment (POC) and the probability of detection (POD), which together will equal an overall probability of success (POS).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Ultimately this serves as a practical application of probability distribution in order to provide the swiftest and most expedient method of rescue, saving both lives and resources.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation is commonly used to evaluate the risk and uncertainty that would affect the outcome of different decision options.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods in finance are often used to evaluate investments in projects at a business unit or corporate level, or other financial valuations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] They can be used to model project schedules, where simulations aggregate estimates for worst-case, best-case, and most likely durations for each task to determine outcomes for the overall project.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in option pricing, default risk analysis.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Additionally, they can be used to estimate the financial impact of medical interventions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo approach was used for evaluating the potential value of a proposed program to help female petitioners in Wisconsin be successful in their applications for harassment and domestic abuse restraining orders.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] It was proposed to help women succeed in their petitions by providing them with greater advocacy thereby potentially reducing the risk of rape and physical assault.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] However, there were many variables in play that could not be estimated perfectly, including the effectiveness of restraining orders, the success rate of petitioners both with and without advocacy, and many others.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The study ran trials that varied these variables to come up with an overall estimate of the success level of the proposed program as a whole.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo approach had also been used to simulate the number of book publications based on book genre in Malaysia.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation utilized previous published National Book publication data and book's price according to book genre in the local market.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo results were used to determine what kind of book genre that Malaysians are fond of and was used to compare book publications between Malaysia and Japan.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Nassim Nicholas Taleb writes about Monte Carlo generators in his 2001 book *Fooled by Randomness* as a real instance of the reverse Turing test: a human can be declared unintelligent if their writing cannot be told apart from a generated one.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In general, the Monte Carlo methods are used in mathematics to solve various problems by generating suitable random numbers (see also Random number generation) and observing that fraction of the numbers that obeys some property or properties.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The method is useful for obtaining numerical solutions to problems too complicated to solve analytically.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The most common application of the Monte Carlo method is Monte Carlo integration.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Deterministic numerical integration algorithms work well in a small number of dimensions, but encounter two problems when the functions have many variables.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] First, the number of function evaluations needed increases rapidly with the number of dimensions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] For example, if 10 evaluations provide adequate accuracy in one dimension, then 10100 points are needed for 100 dimensions—far too many to be computed.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] This is called the curse of dimensionality.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Second, the boundary of a multidimensional region may be very complicated, so it may not be feasible to reduce the problem to an iterated integral.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] 100 dimensions is by no means unusual, since in many physical problems, a "dimension" is equivalent to a degree of freedom.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods provide a way out of this exponential increase in computation time.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] As long as the function in question is reasonably well-behaved, it can be estimated by randomly selecting points in 100-dimensional space, and taking some kind of average of the function values at these points.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] By the central limit theorem, this method displays $\scriptstyle 1/{\sqrt {N}}$ convergence—i.e., quadrupling the number of sampled points halves the error, regardless of the number of dimensions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A refinement of this method, known as importance sampling in statistics, involves sampling the points randomly, but more frequently where the integrand is large.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] To do this precisely one would have to already know the integral, but one can approximate the integral by an integral of a similar function or use adaptive routines such as stratified sampling, recursive stratified sampling, adaptive umbrella sampling or the VEGAS algorithm.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A similar approach, the quasi-Monte Carlo method, uses low-discrepancy sequences.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] These sequences "fill" the area better and sample the most important points more frequently, so quasi-Monte Carlo methods can often converge on the integral more quickly.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Another class of methods for sampling points in a volume is to simulate random walks over it (Markov chain Monte Carlo).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Such methods include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, Gibbs sampling, Wang and Landau algorithm, and interacting type MCMC methodologies such as the sequential Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Another powerful and very popular application for random numbers in numerical simulation is in numerical optimization.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The problem is to minimize (or maximize) functions of some vector that often has many dimensions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Many problems can be phrased in this way: for example, a computer chess program could be seen as trying to find the set of, say, 10 moves that produces the best evaluation function at the end.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In the traveling salesman problem the goal is to minimize distance traveled.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] There are also applications to engineering design, such as multidisciplinary design optimization.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] It has been applied with quasi-one-dimensional models to solve particle dynamics problems by efficiently exploring large configuration space.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Reference is a comprehensive review of many issues related to simulation and optimization.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The traveling salesman problem is what is called a conventional optimization problem.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] That is, all the facts (distances between each destination point) needed to determine the optimal path to follow are known with certainty and the goal is to run through the possible travel choices to come up with the one with the lowest total distance.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] If instead of the goal being to minimize the total distance traveled to visit each desired destination but rather to minimize the total time needed to reach each destination, this goes beyond conventional optimization since travel time is inherently uncertain (traffic jams, time of day, etc.).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Probabilistic formulation of inverse problems leads to the definition of a probability distribution in the model space.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] This probability distribution combines prior information with new information obtained by measuring some observable parameters (data).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] As, in the general case, the theory linking data with model parameters is nonlinear, the posterior probability in the model space may not be easy to describe (it may be multimodal, some moments may not be defined, etc.).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] When analyzing an inverse problem, obtaining a maximum likelihood model is usually not sufficient, as normally information on the resolution power of the data is desired.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In the general case many parameters are modeled, and an inspection of the marginal probability densities of interest may be impractical, or even useless.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] But it is possible to pseudorandomly generate a large collection of models according to the posterior probability distribution and to analyze and display the models in such a way that information on the relative likelihoods of model properties is conveyed to the spectator.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] This can be accomplished by means of an efficient Monte Carlo method, even in cases where no explicit formula for the *a priori* distribution is available.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The best-known importance sampling method, the Metropolis algorithm, can be generalized, and this gives a method that allows analysis of (possibly highly nonlinear) inverse problems with complex *a priori* information and data with an arbitrary noise distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Popular exposition of the Monte Carlo Method was conducted by McCracken.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The method's general philosophy was discussed by Elishakoff and Grüne-Yanoff and Weirich.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] quasi-random numbers, showing the first 10 (red), 100 (red+blue) and 256 (red+blue+green) points from the sequence.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Points from Sobol sequence are more evenly distributed.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] In numerical analysis, the **quasi-Monte Carlo method** is a method for numerical integration and solving some other problems using low-discrepancy sequences (also called quasi-random sequences or sub-random sequences) to achieve variance reduction.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] This is in contrast to the regular Monte Carlo method or Monte Carlo integration, which are based on sequences of pseudorandom numbers.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo and quasi-Monte Carlo methods are stated in a similar way.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Since we are integrating over the *s*-dimensional unit cube, each *x**i* is a vector of *s* elements.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] The difference between quasi-Monte Carlo and Monte Carlo is the way the *x**i* are chosen.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Quasi-Monte Carlo uses a low-discrepancy sequence such as the Halton sequence, the Sobol sequence, or the Faure sequence, whereas Monte Carlo uses a pseudorandom sequence.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] The advantage of using low-discrepancy sequences is a faster rate of convergence.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Quasi-Monte Carlo has a rate of convergence close to O(1/*N*), whereas the rate for the Monte Carlo method is O(*N*−0.5).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] The Quasi-Monte Carlo method recently became popular in the area of mathematical finance or computational finance.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] In these areas, high-dimensional numerical integrals, where the integral should be evaluated within a threshold ε, occur frequently.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Hence, the Monte Carlo method and the quasi-Monte Carlo method are beneficial in these situations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] The approximation error of the quasi-Monte Carlo method is bounded by a term proportional to the discrepancy of the set *x*1, ..., *x**N*.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] where *V*(*f*) is the Hardy–Krause variation of the function *f* (see Morokoff and Caflisch (1995) for the detailed definitions).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] where *Q* is a rectangular solid in [0,1]*s* with sides parallel to the coordinate axes.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] The inequality $|\varepsilon |\leq V(f)D_{N}$ can be used to show that the error of the approximation by the quasi-Monte Carlo method is $O\left({\frac {(\log N)^{s}}{N}}\right)$ , whereas the Monte Carlo method has a probabilistic error of $O\left({\frac {1}{\sqrt {N}}}\right)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Thus, for sufficiently large N , quasi-Monte Carlo will always outperform random Monte Carlo.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] However, $\log(N)^{s}$ grows exponentially quickly with the dimension, meaning a poorly-chosen sequence can be much worse than Monte Carlo in high dimensions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] In practice, it is almost always possible to select an appropriate low-discrepancy sequence, or apply an appropriate transformation to the integrand, to ensure that quasi-Monte Carlo performs at least as well as Monte Carlo (and often much better).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] For one-dimensional integration, quadrature methods such as the trapezoidal rule, Simpson's rule, or Newton–Cotes formulas are known to be efficient if the function is smooth.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] These approaches can be also used for multidimensional integrations by repeating the one-dimensional integrals over multiple dimensions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] However, the number of function evaluations grows exponentially as *s*, the number of dimensions, increases.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Hence, a method that can overcome this curse of dimensionality should be used for multidimensional integrations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] The standard Monte Carlo method is frequently used when the quadrature methods are difficult or expensive to implement.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo and quasi-Monte Carlo methods are accurate and relatively fast when the dimension is high, up to 300 or higher.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Morokoff and Caflisch studied the performance of Monte Carlo and quasi-Monte Carlo methods for integration.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] In the paper, Halton, Sobol, and Faure sequences for quasi-Monte Carlo are compared with the standard Monte Carlo method using pseudorandom sequences.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] They found that the Halton sequence performs best for dimensions up to around 6; the Sobol sequence performs best for higher dimensions; and the Faure sequence, while outperformed by the other two, still performs better than a pseudorandom sequence.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] However, Morokoff and Caflisch gave examples where the advantage of the quasi-Monte Carlo is less than expected theoretically.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Still, in the examples studied by Morokoff and Caflisch, the quasi-Monte Carlo method did yield a more accurate result than the Monte Carlo method with the same number of points.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Morokoff and Caflisch remark that the advantage of the quasi-Monte Carlo method is greater if the integrand is smooth, and the number of dimensions *s* of the integral is small.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] In order to overcome some of these difficulties, we can use a randomized quasi-Monte Carlo method.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Since the low discrepancy sequence are not random, but deterministic, quasi-Monte Carlo method can be seen as a deterministic algorithm or derandomized algorithm.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] In this case, we only have the bound (e.g., *ε* ≤ *V*(*f*) *D**N*) for error, and the error is hard to estimate.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] In order to recover our ability to analyze and estimate the variance, we can randomize the method (see randomization for the general idea).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] The resulting method is called the randomized quasi-Monte Carlo method and can be also viewed as a variance reduction technique for the standard Monte Carlo method.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Among several methods, the simplest transformation procedure is through random shifting.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Let {*x*1,...,*x**N*} be the point set from the low discrepancy sequence.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] We sample *s*-dimensional random vector *U* and mix it with {*x*1, ..., *x**N*}.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] If we have *R* replications for Monte Carlo, sample s-dimensional random vector U for each replication.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Randomization allows to give an estimate of the variance while still using quasi-random sequences.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/quasi-monte-carlo-method] Compared to pure quasi Monte-Carlo, the number of samples of the quasi random sequence will be divided by *R* for an equivalent computational cost, which reduces the theoretical convergence rate.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] In numerical analysis and computational statistics, **rejection sampling** is a basic technique used to generate observations from a distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] It is also commonly called the **acceptance-rejection method** or "accept-reject algorithm" and is a type of exact simulation method.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The method works for any distribution in $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ with a density.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling is based on the observation that to sample a random variable in one dimension, one can perform a uniformly random sampling of the two-dimensional Cartesian graph, and keep the samples in the region under the graph of its density function.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Note that this property can be extended to *N*-dimension functions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Sample $U\sim \mathrm {Unif} (0,1)$ , independently of X .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] If $W<M\times U$ , reject X and repeat from step 1.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The algorithm will take an average of ${\frac {M}{\int f_{\varpropto }(y)dy}}$ rejections to obtain a sample.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] To visualize the motivation behind rejection sampling, imagine graphing the probability density function (PDF) of a random variable onto a large rectangular board and throwing darts at it.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Assume that the darts are uniformly distributed around the board.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Now remove all of the darts that are outside the area under the curve.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The remaining darts will be distributed uniformly within the area under the curve, and the x ‑positions of these darts will be distributed according to the random variable's density.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] This is because there is the most room for the darts to land where the curve is highest and thus the probability density is greatest.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The visualization just described is equivalent to a particular form of rejection sampling where the "proposal distribution" is uniform.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The general form of rejection sampling assumes that the board is not necessarily rectangular but is shaped according to the density of some proposal distribution (not necessarily normalized to 1 ) that we know how to sample from (for example, using inversion sampling).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Its shape must be at least as high at every point as the distribution we want to sample from, so that the former completely encloses the latter.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Otherwise, there would be parts of the curved area we want to sample from that could never be reached.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Draw a vertical line at this x ‑position, up to the y-value of the probability density function of the proposal distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] If the sampled value is greater than the value of the desired distribution at this vertical line, reject the x ‑value and return to step 1; else the x ‑value is a sample from the desired distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] This algorithm can be used to sample from the area under any curve, regardless of whether the function integrates to 1.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] In fact, scaling a function by a constant has no effect on the sampled x ‑positions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Thus, the algorithm can be used to sample from a distribution whose normalizing constant is unknown, which is common in computational statistics.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] In the following analysis we assume for simplicity that $f\equiv f_{\varpropto }$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The rejection sampling method generates sampling values from a target distribution with probability density function $f(x)$ by using a proposal distribution with probability density $g(x)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The idea is that one can generate a sample value from f by instead sampling from g and accepting the sample from f with probability $f(x)/(Mg(x))$ , repeating the draws from g until a value is accepted.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] M here is a constant, finite bound on the likelihood ratio $f(x)/g(x)$ , satisfying $M<\infty$ over the support of f ; in other words, M must satisfy $f(x)\leq Mg(x)$ for all values of x .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Note that this requires that the support of g must include the support of f —in other words, $g(x)>0$ whenever $f(x)>0$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The validation of this method is the envelope principle: when simulating the pair ${\textstyle (x,v=u\cdot Mg(x))}$ , one produces a uniform simulation over the subgraph of ${\textstyle Mg(x)}$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] This means that, with enough replicates, the algorithm generates a sample from the desired distribution $f(x)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] There are a number of extensions to this algorithm, such as the Metropolis algorithm.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] This method relates to the general field of Monte Carlo techniques, including Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithms that also use a proxy distribution to achieve simulation from the target distribution $f(x)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] It forms the basis for algorithms such as the Metropolis algorithm.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The number of samples required from g to obtain an accepted value thus follows a geometric distribution with probability $1/M$ , which has mean M .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Intuitively, M is the expected number of the iterations that are needed, as a measure of the computational complexity of the algorithm.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] When M is chosen closer to one, the unconditional acceptance probability is higher the less that ratio varies, since M is the upper bound for the likelihood ratio ${\textstyle f(x)/g(x)}$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] In practice, a value of M closer to 1 is preferred as it implies fewer rejected samples, on average, and thus fewer iterations of the algorithm.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] In this sense, one prefers to have M as small as possible (while still satisfying $f(x)\leq Mg(x)$ , which suggests that $g(x)$ should generally resemble $f(x)$ in some way.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Note, however, that M cannot be equal to 1: such would imply that $f(x)=g(x)$ , i.e. that the target and proposal distributions are actually the same distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling is most often used in cases where the form of $f(x)$ makes sampling difficult.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] A single iteration of the rejection algorithm requires sampling from the proposal distribution, drawing from a uniform distribution, and evaluating the $f(x)/(Mg(x))$ expression.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling is thus more efficient than some other method whenever M times the cost of these operations—which is the expected cost of obtaining a sample with rejection sampling—is lower than the cost of obtaining a sample using the other method.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling can be far more efficient compared with the naive methods in some situations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The problem is this sampling can be difficult and inefficient, if ${\textstyle \mathbb {P} (X\in A)\approx 0}$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The expected number of iterations would be ${\frac {1}{\mathbb {P} (X\in A)}}$ , which could be close to infinity.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Moreover, even when you apply the Rejection sampling method, it is always hard to optimize the bound M for the likelihood ratio.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] More often than not, M is large and the rejection rate is high, the algorithm can be very inefficient.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The Natural Exponential Family (if it exists), also known as exponential tilting, provides a class of proposal distributions that can lower the computation complexity, the value of M and speed up the computations (see examples: working with Natural Exponential Families).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Given a random variable $X\sim F(\cdot )$ , $F(x)=\mathbb {P} (X\leq x)$ is the target distribution.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Assume for simplicity, the density function can be explicitly written as $f(x)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] where $\psi (\theta )=\log \left(\mathbb {E} \exp(\theta X)\right)$ and ${\displaystyle \Theta =\{\theta$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Clearly, $\{F_{\theta }(\cdot )\}_{\theta \in \Theta }$ , is from a natural exponential family.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] It is easy to derive the cumulant-generation function of the proposal and therefore the proposal's cumulants.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The goal is to sample $X|X\in \left[b,\infty \right]$ , where $b>\mu$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] holds, accept the value of X ; if not, continue sampling new ${\textstyle X\sim _{i.i.d.}\mathrm {N} (\mu +\theta ^{*}\sigma ^{2},\sigma ^{2})}$ and new ${\textstyle U\sim \mathrm {Unif} (0,1)}$ until acceptance.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] In general, exponential tilting a parametric class of proposal distribution, solves the optimization problems conveniently, with its useful properties that directly characterize the distribution of the proposal.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] For this type of problem, to simulate X conditionally on $X\in A$ , among the class of simple distributions, the trick is to use natural exponential family, which helps to gain some control over the complexity and considerably speed up the computation.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Indeed, there are deep mathematical reasons for using natural exponential family.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling requires knowing the target distribution (specifically, ability to evaluate target PDF at any point).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling can lead to a lot of unwanted samples being taken if the function being sampled is highly concentrated in a certain region, for example a function that has a spike at some location.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] For many distributions, this problem can be solved using an adaptive extension (see adaptive rejection sampling), or with an appropriate change of variables with the method of the ratio of uniforms.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] In addition, as the dimensions of the problem get larger, the ratio of the embedded volume to the "corners" of the embedding volume tends towards zero, thus a lot of rejections can take place before a useful sample is generated, thus making the algorithm inefficient and impractical.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] In high dimensions, it is necessary to use a different approach, typically a Markov chain Monte Carlo method such as Metropolis sampling or Gibbs sampling.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] If $W_{1}+\cdots +W_{t}<M$ , reject X and repeat from step 1.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] It can be shown that, as $M\rightarrow \infty$ , the output variable of the algorithm $X=X_{M}$ converges in distribution to the desired target with density f .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Another approach that requires no knowledge of the optimal bounding constant $\sup _{x}{\frac {f_{\varpropto }(x)}{g(x)}}$ is the *empirical supremum rejection sampling* method.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] For many distributions, finding a proposal distribution that includes the given distribution without a lot of wasted space is difficult.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Instead of a single uniform envelope density function, use a piecewise linear density function as your envelope instead.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] We can take even further advantage of the (log) concavity requirement, to potentially avoid the cost of evaluating $f\left(x\right)$ when your sample *is* accepted.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The method essentially involves successively determining an envelope of straight-line segments that approximates the logarithm better and better while still remaining above the curve, starting with a fixed number of segments (possibly just a single tangent line).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Sampling from a truncated exponential random variable is straightforward.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Just take the log of a uniform random variable (with appropriate interval and corresponding truncation).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Unfortunately, ARS can only be applied for sampling from log-concave target densities.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] For this reason, several extensions of ARS have been proposed in literature for tackling non-log-concave target distributions.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] Furthermore, different combinations of ARS and the Metropolis-Hastings method have been designed in order to obtain a universal sampler that builds a self-tuning proposal densities (i.e., a proposal automatically constructed and adapted to the target).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] This class of methods are often called as **Adaptive Rejection Metropolis Sampling (ARMS) algorithms**.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/rejection-sampling] The resulting adaptive techniques can be always applied but the generated samples are correlated in this case (although the correlation vanishes quickly to zero as the number of iterations grows).
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] In mathematics, more specifically in the theory of Monte Carlo methods, **variance reduction** is a procedure used to increase the precision of the estimates obtained for a given simulation or computational effort.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] Every output random variable from the simulation is associated with a variance which limits the precision of the simulation results.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] In order to make a simulation statistically efficient, i.e., to obtain a greater precision and smaller confidence intervals for the output random variable of interest, variance reduction techniques can be used.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] For simulation with black-box models subset simulation and line sampling can also be used.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] Under these headings are a variety of specialized techniques; for example, particle transport simulations make extensive use of "weight windows" and "splitting/Russian roulette" techniques, which are a form of importance sampling.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] Suppose one wants to compute $z:=E(Z)$ with the random variable Z defined on the probability space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] Under further mild conditions such as $var(Z)<\infty$ , a central limit theorem will apply such that for large $n\rightarrow \infty$ , the distribution of ${\overline {z}}$ converges to a normal distribution with mean z and standard error $\sigma /{\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] The common random numbers variance reduction technique is a popular and useful variance reduction technique which applies when we are comparing two or more alternative configurations (of a system) instead of investigating a single configuration.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] CRN has also been called *correlated sampling*, *matched streams* or *matched pairs*.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] CRN requires synchronization of the random number streams, which ensures that in addition to using the same random numbers to simulate all configurations, a specific random number used for a specific purpose in one configuration is used for exactly the same purpose in all other configurations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] For example, in queueing theory, if we are comparing two different configurations of tellers in a bank, we would want the (random) time of arrival of the *N-*th customer to be generated using the same draw from a random number stream for both configurations.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] Suppose $X_{1j}$ and $X_{2j}$ are the observations from the first and second configurations on the *j-*th independent replication.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] In case of independent sampling, i.e., no common random numbers used then Cov(*X*1*j*, *X*2*j*) = 0.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] But if we succeed to induce an element of positive correlation between *X*1 and *X*2 such that Cov(*X*1*j*, *X*2*j*) > 0, it can be seen from the equation above that the variance is reduced.
[src:monte-carlo-simulation/variance-reduction] It can also be observed that if the CRN induces a negative correlation, i.e., Cov(*X*1*j*, *X*2*j*) < 0, this technique can actually backfire, where the variance is increased and not decreased (as intended).
